K{\footnote How to do ?___;Circuit__;Layout}
+{\footnote howtodo:020}
\keepn \cf0 \f1\fs48 {\uldb \{bml LOKON.BMP\}}{\v Topic43}\qc How to build a circuit ?\par\pard\tx360\qc \f1\fs32 \b A new circuit window\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 First you need a work window for your circuit.\par
\{bmc HOWNEWLA.SHG\}\par
For that you have to select \i New\i0  in the \i File\i0  menu. Then you have to select \i circuit\i0 .\par
\{bmc HOWLAY.SHG\}\par
A new circuit window appears. It is called \i Circuit\i0 .\par
\par
\qc \f1\fs32 \b Full screen\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 To work better with the window you can raise it. You can do this by draging the border to a larger size. But it's best to work in full screen mode.\par
To bring  LoKon to full screen mode, you have to select the \{bmc HOWFULL.SHG\} up arrow.\par
Do the same to bring your circuit window to full screen.\par
\par
\qc \f1\fs32 \b Insert an element\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 LoKon has many enclosed elements that are saved in several files.\par
Now we insert such an element into the circuit.\par
Choose the \{bmc HOWELEBU.SHG\} element button from the speed bar.\par
\{bmc HOWELEMN.SHG\}\par
You also can select the menu command \i Element->Elements...\i0  or press the keys \i Alt+Space\i0 .\par
Then the following dialog box appears:\par
\{bmc HOWELECE.SHG\}\par
To include an element file press the \{bmc HOWELNEW.SHG\} button.\par
\{bmc NEWELEFI.SHG\}\par
In this dialog box you have to choose the alias name of the element file (here: Elements), that you want to include into your circuit. Confirm with \b OK\b0 .\par
You can also select an alias name width a double click.\par
Include the file Elements into you circuit. You can then use the elements in the list Elements in you circuit.\par
\{bmc ELECHOOS.SHG\}\par
Select \i Elements\i0  in the file list. The elements of the the file Elements then appear in the elements list.\par
You can select an element (here the AND gate) in two different ways:\par
{\li360}1. Select the element with the mouse button, then press the \{bmc OKBUTTON.SHG\} button.\par
2. Double click the element with the mouse button.\par
\par\pard\tx360Now you have to find a position for your element. Then fix it there with the left mouse button.\par
\par
\qc \f1\fs32 \b Move an element\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 You have just moved an element.\par
To move an element in the circuit select it with the left mouse button. The mouse cursor then looks like \{bmc MOVECUR.BMP \} .\par
Move the element to the desired position (by pressing the left mouse button). Then let the button go. If you press the right mouse button while moving the element (while pressing the left mouse button), the element turns by 90 degrees clockwise.\par
\cf12 Warning:\cf0  If the mouse pointer looks like \{bmc MOVECUR2.BMP \} , another element is touched. If you let the left mouse button go, the element is moved back to the old position. If you wanted to insert a new element and it touches another element it is not inserted in the circuit.\par
\par
\qc \f1\fs32 \b Insert a copy of an element\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 \{bmc HOWAND.SHG\}\par
By selecting the this menu command (or by pressing the keys \i Ctrl+Space\i0 ) you can insert a copy of the last moved element.\par
In the same way you can insert a copy of an existing element into the circuit.\par
For that select it with the left mouse button (don't move the mouse, otherwise you move the element). The upper menu command then changes. It always has the name of the last selected element.\par
\par
\qc \f1\fs32 \b Connect elements\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 \{bmc HOWCON.SHG\}\par
In the example circuit, an input (red) and an output (green) were circled.\par
You can connect them by selecting one of them\{bmc CONNCUR.BMP \} , pressing the left move button and pulling the connection to the other input/output.\par
A connection is only made if the mouse pointer is over an input/ouput that is still free (the mouse\par
pointer again must look like \{bmc CONNCUR.BMP \} ). A connection is connected with the input/output of the element.\par
It is not fixed at a certain position.\par
\par
\qc \f1\fs32 \b Set a connection point\b0 \par
\ql \f0\fs24 If you lay the end of a connection onto another connection \{bmc CONNCUR4.BMP \} , a connection point is created automatically.\par
